                    <h2 class=3D"firstH2">Triangle Figure
                        <br>
                        Angle-Side-Angle (ASA)
                    </h2>
                    <p>
                        <img src=3D"https://www.calculatorsoup.com/images/t=
riangletheorems/triangle-asa.png" alt=3D"Triangle Diagram for Angle-Side-An=
gle with Angles A, B and C and sides opposite those angles a, b and c respe=
ctively" width=3D"200" height=3D"150">
                        <br>
                        A =3D angle A
                        <br>
                        B =3D angle B
                        <br>
                        C =3D angle C
                        <br>
                        a =3D side a
                        <br>
                        b =3D side b
                        <br>
                        c =3D side c
                        <br>
                        <br>
                        P =3D perimeter
                        <br>
                        s =3D semi-perimeter
                        <br>
                        K =3D area
                        <br>
                        r =3D radius of inscribed circle
                        <br>
                        R =3D radius of circumscribed circle
                    </p><!-- InstanceEndEditable -->
                                <!-- InstanceBeginEditable name=3D"content"=
 -->
                <p>Each calculation option, shown below, has sub-bullets th=
at list the sequence of methods used in this calculator to solve for unknow=
n angle and side values including
                    <a href=3D"https://www.calculatorsoup.com/calculators/g=
eometry-plane/triangle-theorems.php#anglesum">Sum of Angles</a> in a Triang=
le, <a href=3D"https://www.calculatorsoup.com/calculators/geometry-plane/tr=
iangle-theorems.php#law_of_sines">Law of Sines</a> and
                    <a href=3D"https://www.calculatorsoup.com/calculators/g=
eometry-plane/triangle-theorems.php#law_of_cosines">Law of Cosines</a>.&nbs=
p; These are NOT the ONLY sequences you could use to solve these types of p=
roblems.
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>See also these Trigonometry Calculators:</s=
trong></li>
                    <li>
                        <a href=3D"https://www.calculatorsoup.com/calculato=
rs/geometry-plane/triangle-law-of-cosines.php">Law of Cosines Calculator</a=
>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <a href=3D"https://www.calculatorsoup.com/calculato=
rs/geometry-plane/triangle-law-of-sines.php">Law of Sines Calculator</a>
                    </li>
                </ul>
                <h2>Solving Triangle Theorems</h2>
                <div style=3D"text-align:center">
                    <img id=3D"trianglebase" src=3D"https://www.calculators=
oup.com/images/triangletheorems/triangle-base.gif" width=3D"200" height=3D"=
150" alt=3D"Base Triangle ABC">
                </div>
                <h3 id=3D"aaa">AAA is Angle, Angle, Angle </h3>
                <p>Specifying the three angles of a triangle does not uniqu=
ely identify one triangle. Therefore, specifying two angles of a tringle al=
lows you to calculate the third angle only.
                </p><p>Given the sizes of 2 angles of a triangle you can ca=
lculate the size of the third angle. The total will equal 180=C2=B0 or
                    <span class=3D"pi">=CF=80</span> radians.
                </p><p>C =3D 180=C2=B0 - A - B (in degrees)</p>
                <p>C =3D <span class=3D"pi">=CF=80</span> - A - B (in radia=
ns)</p>
                <h3 id=3D"aas">AAS is Angle, Angle, Side </h3>
                <p>Given the size of 2 angles and 1 side opposite one of th=
e given angles, you can calculate the sizes of the remaining 1 angle and 2 =
sides.
                </p><p>use the Sum of Angles Rule to find the other angle, =
then</p>
                <p>use The Law of Sines to solve for each of the other two =
sides.</p>
                <h3 id=3D"asa">ASA is Angle, Side, Angle </h3>
                <p>Given the size of 2 angles and the size of the side that=
 is in between those 2 angles you can calculate the sizes of the remaining =
1 angle and 2 sides.
                </p><p>use the Sum of Angles Rule to find the other angle, =
then</p>
                <p>use The Law of Sines to solve for each of the other two =
sides.</p>
                <h3 id=3D"ass">ASS (or SSA) is Angle, Side, Side </h3>
                <p>Given the size of 2 sides (a and c where a &lt; c) and t=
he size of the angle A that is not in between those 2 sides you might be ab=
le to calculate the sizes of the remaining 1 side and 2 angles, depending o=
n the following conditions.
                </p><p>For <strong>A =E2=89=A5 90=C2=B0 (A =E2=89=A5 <span =
class=3D"pi">=CF=80</span>/2)</strong>:
                </p><p>If <strong>a =E2=89=A4 c</strong> there there are no=
 possible triangles</p>
                <p>Example:
                    <br>
                    <img src=3D"https://www.calculatorsoup.com/images/trian=
gletheorems/triangle-ass-01.png" width=3D"200" height=3D"150" alt=3D"ASS Th=
eorem A &gt; 90 and side a less than side c">
                </p>
                <p>If <strong>a &gt; c</strong> there is 1 possible solutio=
n</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>use The Law of Sines to solve for angle C</li>
                    <li>use the Sum of Angles Rule to find the other angle,=
 B</li>
                    <li>use The Law of Sines to solve for the last side, b<=
/li>
                    <li>Example:
                        <br>
                        <img src=3D"https://www.calculatorsoup.com/images/t=
riangletheorems/triangle-ass-02.png" width=3D"200" height=3D"150" alt=3D"AS=
S Theorem A &gt; 90 and side a greater than side c">
                    </li>
                </ul>
                <p>For <strong>A &lt; 90=C2=B0 (A &lt; <span class=3D"pi">=
=CF=80</span>/2)</strong>:
                </p><p>If <strong>a =E2=89=A5 c</strong> there is 1 possibl=
e solution</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>use The Law of Sines to solve for angle C</li>
                    <li>use the Sum of Angles Rule to find the other angle,=
 B</li>
                    <li>use The Law of Sines to solve for the last side, b<=
/li>
                    <li>Example:
                        <br>
                        <img src=3D"https://www.calculatorsoup.com/images/t=
riangletheorems/triangle-ass-03.png" width=3D"200" height=3D"150" alt=3D"AS=
S Theorem A &lt; 90 and side a greater than side c">
                    </li>
                </ul>
                <p>If <strong>a &lt; c</strong> we have 3 potential situati=
ons.&nbsp; "If
                    <strong>sin(A) &lt; a/c</strong>, there are two possibl=
e triangles satisfying the given conditions. If
                    <strong>sin(A) =3D a/c</strong>, there is one possible =
triangle. If
                    <strong>sin(A) &gt; a/c</strong>, there are no possible=
 triangles." <sup>[1]</sup>
                </p><p><strong>sin(A) &lt; a/c</strong>, there are two poss=
ible triangles
                    <br>
                </p><p>solve for the 2 possible values of the 3rd side b =
=3D c*cos(A) =C2=B1 =E2=88=9A[ a<sup>2</sup> - c<sup>2</sup> sin<sup>2</sup=
> (A) ]<sup>[1]</sup>
                </p>
                <p>for each set of solutions, use The Law of Cosines to sol=
ve for each of the other two angles</p>
                <p>present 2 full solutions</p>
                <p>Example:
                    <br>
                    <img src=3D"https://www.calculatorsoup.com/images/trian=
gletheorems/triangle-ass_2.png" width=3D"200" height=3D"150" alt=3D"triangl=
e ass theorem with 2 solutions">
                    <br>
                </p>
                <p><strong>sin(A) =3D a/c</strong>, there is one possible t=
riangle
                    <br>
                </p><p>use The Law of Sines to solve for an angle, C</p>
                <p>use the Sum of Angles Rule to find the other angle, B</p=
>
                <p>use The Law of Sines to solve for the last side, b</p>
                <p>Example:
                    <br>
                    <img src=3D"https://www.calculatorsoup.com/images/trian=
gletheorems/triangle-ass_1.png" width=3D"200" height=3D"150" alt=3D"triangl=
e ass theorem with 1 solution">
                </p>
                <p><strong>sin(A) &gt; a/c</strong>, there are no possible =
triangles
                    <br>
                </p><p>Error Notice: sin(A) &gt; a/c so there are no soluti=
ons and no triangle!</p>
                <p>Example:
                    <br>
                    <img src=3D"https://www.calculatorsoup.com/images/trian=
gletheorems/triangle-ass_0.png" alt=3D"triangle ass theorem with 0 solution=
s" width=3D"200" height=3D"150">
                </p>
                <h3 id=3D"sas">SAS is Side, Angle, Side </h3>
                <p>Given the size of 2 sides (c and a) and the size of the =
angle B that is in between those 2 sides you can calculate the sizes of the=
 remaining 1 side and 2 angles.
                </p><p>use The Law of Cosines to solve for the remaining si=
de, b</p>
                <p>determine which side, a or c, is smallest and use the La=
w of Sines to solve for the size of the opposite angle, A or C respectively=
.<sup>[2]</sup>
                </p>
                <p>use the Sum of Angles Rule to find the last angle</p>
                <h3 id=3D"sss"><strong>SSS is Side, Side, Side</strong></h3=
>
                <p>Given the sizes of the 3 sides you can calculate the siz=
es of all 3 angles in the triangle.
                </p><p>use The Law of Cosines to solve for the angles.&nbsp=
; You&nbsp;could also use the Sum of Angles Rule to find the final angle on=
ce you know 2 of them.</p>
                <h2 id=3D"anglesum">Sum of Angles in a Triangle</h2>
                <p>In Degrees A + B + C =3D 180=C2=B0</p>
                <p>In Radians A + B + C =3D <span class=3D"pi">=CF=80</span=
></p>
                <h2 id=3D"law_of_sines">Law of Sines</h2>
                <p>If a, b and c are the lengths of the legs of a triangle =
opposite to the angles A, B and C respectively; then the law of sines state=
s: </p>
                <p>a/sin A =3D b/sin B =3D c/sin C</p>
                <p>Solving, for example, for an angle, A =3D sin<sup>-1</su=
p> [ a*sin(B) / b ]</p>
                <h2 id=3D"law_of_cosines">Law of Cosines </h2>
                <p>If a, b and c are the lengths of the legs of a triangle =
opposite to the angles A, B and C respectively; then the law of cosines sta=
tes: </p>
                <p>a<sup>2</sup> =3D c<sup>2</sup> + b<sup>2</sup> - 2bc co=
s A,&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;solving for cos A,&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;cos A =3D ( b<sup=
>2</sup> + c<sup>2</sup> - a<sup>2</sup> ) / 2bc
                </p>
                <p>b<sup>2</sup> =3D a<sup>2</sup> + c<sup>2</sup> - 2ca co=
s B,&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;solving for cos B,&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;cos B =3D ( c<sup=
>2</sup> + a<sup>2</sup> - b<sup>2</sup> ) / 2ca
                </p>
                <p>c<sup>2</sup> =3D b<sup>2</sup> + a<sup>2</sup> - 2ab co=
s C,&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;solving for cos C,&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;cos C =3D ( a<sup=
>2</sup> + b<sup>2</sup> - c<sup>2</sup> ) / 2ab
                </p>
                <p>Solving, for example, for an angle, A =3D cos<sup>-1</su=
p> [ ( b<sup>2</sup> + c<sup>2</sup> - a<sup>2</sup> ) / 2bc ]
                </p>
                <h2>Other Triangle Characteristics</h2>
                <p>Triangle perimeter, P =3D a + b + c</p>
                <p>Triangle semi-perimeter, s =3D 0.5 * (a + b + c)</p>
                <p>Triangle area, K =3D =E2=88=9A[ s*(s-a)*(s-b)*(s-c)]</p>
                <p>Radius of inscribed circle in the triangle, r =3D =E2=88=
=9A[ (s-a)*(s-b)*(s-c) / s ]</p>
                <p>Radius of circumscribed circle around triangle, R =3D (a=
bc) / (4K) </p>
                <h2>References/ Further Reading</h2>
                <p>[1]
                    <a href=3D"http://mathworld.wolfram.com/about/author.ht=
ml">Weisstein, Eric W.</a> "ASS Theorem." From
                    <a href=3D"http://mathworld.wolfram.com/"><em>MathWorld=
